    <h2 class="font-heading text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6 text-center">Why Drainage Matters in the Desert</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">It sounds counterintuitive — drainage problems in a place that gets nine inches of rain a year. But Las Cruces gets most of that rain in violent monsoon bursts between July and September. An inch can fall in a single storm. And the caliche hardpan that sits a few inches to a few feet below the surface won't absorb any of it.</p>
    <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">That water has to go somewhere. Without proper drainage, it pools against your foundation, floods your side yard, erodes slopes, and washes out landscaping you paid good money for. Every monsoon season does a little more damage. Over a few years, that adds up to cracked foundations, settled pavers, and destroyed plantings.</p>
    <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">David is NDS Pro Certified — trained by the largest drainage product manufacturer in the U.S. on proper system design, product selection, and installation. Your drainage system gets engineered to handle what Las Cruces storms actually throw at it, not what looks good on paper.</p>
